Global Execution Context - As soon as whole js program is run the execution context is created and it has 2 components memory and code.

Call stack - it handles everything to manage this execution context creation, deletion and the contro. it maintains the order or execution of execution contexts.

Hoisting - it is where variable and function declarations are moved to the top of their scope before code execution.

Scope - where u can access specific variable and function in our code.

Lexical enviroment - its a local memory alone with lexical enviroment of its parent.

Temporal dead zone - It is the time since the (let or const) variable was hoisted and till it is initialized some value. If anyone tries to access those variables during that zone, Javascript will always throw a reference error (is not defined).

Let and Const - they r maintain in seprate space(Block Scope) not attached to the global space.

Block - it refers to a group of zero or more statements enclosed within curly braces {}.

Closures - It is a combination of a function bundled together and its lexical environment (the scope in which it was declared). This means that an inner function, created within an outer function, retains access to the variables and parameters of that outer function, even after the outer function has completed its execution.

Uses of Closures - Module Design Pattern, currying, Functions like once, memoize, setTimeouts, Itreators, Data hiding and encapsulation

Data hiding - suppose we have variable x and we want to data privavy over it so other functions and other pieces of code cannot access this variable.

Disadvantages of closures - Over consumption of memory, No garbage collected.

Garbage collector - its like a program in the browser or js engine which frees up the unutilize memory.

Anonymous function - A function without a name is called anonymous function.

First class function - The Ability to use function as values as known as First Class Function. it can be passed as arguments to another function and can be returned from the function.

Callback Function - callback function is a function that is passed as an argument to another function.

Event Loop - it enables asynchronous programming by handling tasks efficiently. Since JavaScript is single-threaded, it uses the event loop to manage the execution of multiple tasks without blocking the main thread.

Callback Queue (Task Queue/MacroTask Queue) - When an asynchronous operation handled by a Web API or Node.js API completes, its associated callback function is placed in the callback queue. This queue holds "macro tasks" like (setTimeout, setInterval, and I/O operations).

Microtask Queue - This queue holds "micro tasks," primarily promises (.then(), .catch(), .finally()) and queueMicrotask(). Microtasks have higher priority than macrotasks.

Higher Order Funcion - A function which takes another function as an arguments and return a function called Higher order function.

setInterval - Runs a function repeatedly at every interval (in milliseconds).

useEffect and useLayoutEffect in React are both used for handling side effects, but they differ in their timing. useEffect runs asynchronously after the browser has painted, 
while useLayoutEffect runs synchronously before the browser paints. Use useEffect for most side effects, and useLayoutEffect when you need to measure or manipulate the DOM before the browser repaints, like calculating element dimensions. 

Memory Leak - A memory leak happens when your app keeps memory it no longer needs, so memory usage keeps increasing over time instead of being freed.

SSR vs CSR - CSR renders in the browser after JS loads, while SSR renders HTML on the server before sending it to the browser, improving SEO and first load performance.

CRP (Critical Rendering Path) - CRP is the sequence of steps the browser follows to convert HTML, CSS, and JavaScript into pixels on the screen.
Optimizing CRP focuses on reducing render-blocking resources to show UI faster.

                                HTML loads
                                    ↓
                                CSS loads → CSSOM
                                    ↓
                                JS loads → React starts
                                    ↓
                                JSX → Virtual DOM
                                    ↓
                                Virtual DOM → Real DOM
                                    ↓
                                Browser layout + paint
                                    ↓
                                UI appears 🎉

Webpack - Webpack is a module bundler that builds a dependency graph of your application and bundles JavaScript, CSS, and assets into optimized files.
It makes modern code like JSX, SCSS, and ES6 browser-compatible.

Redux - Redux is a predictable state management library that stores global application state in a single store.
State updates happen through dispatched actions processed by reducers.

Reducers - Reducers are pure functions that take the current state and an action and return a new state.
They define how the application state changes in response to actions.

viewport - The viewport meta tag tells the browser how to scale and size a webpage on different devices, especially mobile screens.

Virtualization - Virtualization in React is a performance optimization technique where only the items visible on the screen are rendered, instead of rendering the entire list or grid at once.
Even if a list has thousands of items, React renders just a small window of items and dynamically updates them as the user scrolls.